deck: Secret Agent Extraordinaire
description:
Origin

After his parents died in a car accident Fireball became the ward of Lord Peter Flint, otherwise known as the world-famous war hero who went by the codename of Warlord.

Fireball was trained by Flint throughout his childhood in various martial arts, weapons usage, and survival techniques, forging him into what would become one of the greatest secret agents of all time.

Creation

Fireball was created in 1976 to be the starring hero of D.C. Thompson's new anthology comic, Bullet, with his original appearance being in the very first issue of said comic.

When Bullet ended Fireball was moved to D.C. Thompson's other comic, Warlord.

Powers

Fireball has no superpowers to speak of, but is an expert martial artist and marksman.
name: Fireball

Origin

One day, police Constable Andy Parker was called to the office of Toronto Police Chief O'Mally. O'Mally was looking for an able young officer to go on an undercover mission to discover the secret identities of the Red Panda and the Flying Squirrel. During the course of his investigation, he wound up assisting the heroes in taking down the criminal organization called the Crime Cabal. While he did not discover their identities, he was sworn in as Agent 51 in the Red Panda's network of operatives.

Other Media

Andy Parker was originally created for the podcast audio drama series "The Red Panda Adventures." Parker first appeared in episode 15, "When Darkness Falls," on November 4, 2006. He is played by Brian Vaughn.

Origin

Jack "Petey" Peters once had his life saved by the Red Panda, which led him to act as an "unofficial" agent in the masked man's network. Peters occaisioally provides information to the Red Panda, and in exchange he often get exclusive stories on the hero's activities. He gained quite a reputation working at the "Toronto Daily Sentinel." When he was hired away to the "Toronto Daily Chronicle" his reputation help change the image of the paper, helping it transform from a dirt-sheet into one of the city's most respected papers.

History

Schmendrick is a bumbling magician who travels with Mommy Fortuna's traveling carnival out of pure necessity. Reduced to entertaining the sightseers who come to the carnival, Schmendrick wants nothing more than to become a true, powerful magician who does not rely on card tricks and cheap illusions.

He sees Mommy Fortuna as an opportunity to gain experience, but when he sees the captured Unicorn for what she is, he decides to free her and join her on her quest.

deck: The love of Captain Cully who joins Schmendrick and the Unicorn.

History

Molly Grue was Captain Cully's common-law wife. As a young woman she had eloped with him, naively attracted to the romance of loving a woodland fugitive and sharing his life. Unfortunately, this turned into years of serving Cully's ragged vagrants as their camp cook.

She seeks a different reality from the one fate decided for her, and when she discovers Schmendrick leaving with the unicorn, she decides to follow them and do whatever she can to help the unicorn in her quest.

deck: Three incredible acrobatic thieves dressed in devil outfits that elude capture from Batman and Robin.
description:
Golden Age

The Three Devils were a group of three former circus acrobats who turned to crime using their abilities to rob jewels and later sell them to fences. Working in Gotham City, they eventually faced up with Batman and Robin. In their first battle the devils managed to escape the dynamic duo.

Batman and Robin fought the devils once more, but the villains escaped again, this time however Robin managed to follow them and found their hideout. The Devils attempt to kill Robin but the boy wonder escapes. Once reunited with Batman, the dynamic duo foil the Devils next caper. In the ensuing battle at the top of the Capitol State Building, one of the Devils falls to and Batman sends the other two to theirs shortly after.

Silver Age

A strikingly similar trio appears in the silver age. Batman and Robin refer to the group as the Daredevils, who are described as three circus acrobats turned jewel thieves. While their costumes are slightly different, the group has the same motif and even use the same fence from the golden age story. At the end of this encounter the Daredevils are arrested.

deck: A golden age Batman villain.
description:
Scorpio is a mysterious figure whose knowledge of science and the black arts was said to create miracles but lead to destitution for everyone he encountered.

He operated out of a castle in the mountains beyond Gotham City, employing several henchmen who wore purple robes and did his bidding. When Batman and Robin confronted Scorpio, he imprisoned them and then attempted to execute them. Batman was able to defeat Scorpio and expose his fraud scheme.
name: Scorpio

deck: A golden age Batman character
description:
Paul Bodin, a retired circus escape artist, mentored Batman in the art of lock picking.

When his daughter is kidnapped, he becomes The Human Key and is forced to commit robberies for a gang of criminals. Bodin's skills allow the thieves to go on a crime spree as they defy the police and rob safes that were thought impenetrable.

Batman and Robin finally apprehend the gang, rescue Bodin's daughter, and ensure that he is exonerated from the crimes he was forced to commit.
name: The Human Key

deck: A golden age Batman villain
description:
History

David Wist was an jeweler who excelled in watch repair. While known to most of Gotham's citizens as real craftsman, Wist wanted to join Frenchy Day's gang but was turned down despite his lock picking skills. In an effort to prove himself as a notable thief, Wist attempted to rob millionaire Jan Major, but was foiled by Batman and Robin. When the dynamic duo chased the would be thief he ran into an Ultra Nuclear Fission Lab and was bombarded with radiation. Wist awoke in a pile of rubble and discovered that his body had somehow turned him into a human magnet.With his new found powers Wist intended to become Gotham's greatest criminal, the Human Magnet.

Wist created a costume for his criminal life and then clothing to mask his abilities while he was in his civilian identity. He then put together his own gang and proceeded to rob museums, trains, and casinos, clashing with Batman and Robin at every event and using his electromagnetic powers to always gain the upper hand. Eventually, Wist took over Frenchy Day's gang and beat down Frenchy for his earlier disrespect.

As the Human Magnet's success grew, he began broadcasting threats boasting about where he would strike next. Batman used this information and was able to create a trap* that exploited Wist's magnetic powers and lead to his defeat.

* He got Wist to slap a mosquito.

Golden age-logic.

Powers

David Wist was turned into a human magnet with his left hand holding a negative charge and his right hand a positive charge. Wist was able manipulate large industrial machines and halt trains. He was not able to turn his powers on or off and had to use material to dampen the magnetic charge when not needed.

deck: Expert Archer Who Uses Trick Arrows
description:
Origin

After being sent out to find a story, Clumsy TV reporter Clem Macey fell through a skylight into a strange building filled with Archery paraphernalia, he was then approached by a creepy old man.

The old man pointed out Clem's resemblance to a painting of a man known as "The Black Archer" and led him to a machine which instilled Clem with the spirit, and all the abilities of this legendary character.

Clem decided to use his new found abilities to fight crime.

Creation

The Black Archer first appeared in Tiger, his first appearance being in the 1966 July issue.

Major Story Arcs

Vs The Axe-Man

The Black Archer's first real adventure saw him trying to defeat The Axe-Man, a local gangster who was in the process of taking over as crime boss of the Black Archer's City.

During this arc Black Archer met the small-time crooks Chango and Katt, who would later (partially) reform and help and accompany Black Archer on many of his later adventures.

War in Heaven

After a long hiatus the Black Archer was brought back for 2000AD's Zenith storyline "War in Heaven" a story in which heroes were recruited from many different dimensions to help fight against the evil Lloigar race, a race of creatures which were killing and possessing Superheroes.

Black Archer was one of the few survivors at the end of the storyline.

Powers and Abilities

The Black Archer is an expert archer, he uses many different trick arrows with a range of effects, such as tying up criminals, smoke and gas bombs, or as a grappling hook.

Outside of his archery abilities Black Archer can also glide, and has respectable fighting ability.

When in extreme danger he can call forth "The Black Wind of Fate" which surrounds him in a whirlwind.
name: Black Archer

deck: a Golden Age Batman Villain
description:
Jason Bard is a master trapper, so obsessed with catching his prey that he completely ignores the law and morality while in pursuit of his prey. The criminal is obsessed with animal traps and uses them in his crimes. He considered Batman and Robin the biggest Game of all time but wound up trapped behind bars when he nearly destroyed Gotham city while pursuing the dynamic duo.

He is not to be confused with the Jason Bard who is a member of the Gotham City Police Department. Though both are Batman characters, they have nothing in common outside of their shared name.
name: The Trapper
